Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Caption", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For sets of points that are not too large one can solve the traveling \
salesman problem\[LongDash]find the shortest cycle that visits all the points\
\[LongDash]by using integer linear programming (ILP), available in ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " via the ",
 StyleBox["Minimize", "MR"],
 " function. Given ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " points, introduce a variable ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["x", 
    RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " for each possible edge, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"1", "\[LessEqual]", "i", "<", "j", "\[LessEqual]", "n"}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ", the idea being that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["x", 
     RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]], "=", "1", " "}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " means that one goes from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["i", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["j", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " in the tour. Then create the equations that force ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"0", "\[LessEqual]", 
    SubscriptBox["x", 
     RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]], "\[LessEqual]", "1"}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " and that each vertex has degree exactly 2, and use the objective function \
that sums the product of the distances between points with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["x", 
    RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 "."
}], "Text"]
}, Close]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
Using ILP guarantees that the solutions are integers (and therefore are \
either 0 or 1). The optimal solution to this linear programming problem will \
likely be a set of disjoint cycles, as opposed to a single cycle. The total \
length of that set provides a lower bound on the optimal tour length. One can \
then add equations that destroy the cycles and run the minimizer again in the \
hope that, after not too many iterations of this process, the result will be \
a single cycle. That must then be the optimal TSP solution for the given \
points. For sets of up to 200 points this method works well, in that not too \
many iterations are needed. It is a bit slow for more than 50 points, as can \
be seen in the logarithmic timing chart; thus for this Demonstration the \
cycles for each step have been precomputed.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
The points in these examples are defined by a slight perturbation of the \
Gaussian primes.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Details", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell["\<\
The snapshots show the three iterations required to find the optimal solution \
in the case of 60 points; that requires only three seconds.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The equations used to set the degrees are: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       RowBox[{"j", "=", "1"}], 
       RowBox[{"j", "-", "1"}]], 
      SubscriptBox["x", 
       RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]]}], "+", 
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       RowBox[{"j", "=", 
        RowBox[{"i", "+", "1"}]}], "n"], 
      SubscriptBox["x", 
       RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]]}]}], "=", "2"}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " for each ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"i", "=", "1"}], ",", "\[Ellipsis]", ",", "n"}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". The inequality used to break a cycle ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["C", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
      RowBox[{"j", "\[Element]", "C"}]], 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"j", ">", "i"}], ",", 
        RowBox[{"j", "\[NotElement]", "C"}]}]], 
      SubscriptBox["x", 
       RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]]}]}], "+"}], TraditionalForm]],
   "InlineMath"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
      RowBox[{"j", "\[Element]", "C"}]], 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"j", "<", "i"}], ",", 
        RowBox[{"j", "\[NotElement]", "C"}]}]], 
      SubscriptBox["x", 
       RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]]}]}], "\[GreaterEqual]", "2"}],
    TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". The objective function that is minimized is: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
      RowBox[{"i", "=", "1"}], 
      RowBox[{"n", "-", "1"}]], 
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       RowBox[{"j", "=", 
        RowBox[{"i", "+", "1"}]}], "n"], 
      SubscriptBox["x", 
       RowBox[{"i", "\[InvisibleSpace]", "j"}]]}]}], "||", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["P",
       FontSlant->"Plain"], "i"], "-", 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["P",
       FontSlant->"Plain"], "j"]}], "||"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["P",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "i"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["i", "th"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " point."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For more details, see Chapter 13 of S. Wagon, ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica in Action",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", 3rd ed., New York, Springer, 2010."
}], "Text"]
}, Close]],

